div.div:
Out of curiosity, could you elaborate on this? I still don't understand how the normalizing flows are leveraged.
Sure, sorry! So the original idea was proposed here https://arxiv.org/abs/1711.09268 but the main idea is that we can augment the x and v updates in the leapfrog integrator with these auxiliary functions which are parameterized by RealNVP coupling layers. This generalized leapfrog integrator then takes as input x, v and uses these invertible coupling layers ("normalizing flows") to construct a trajectory, eventually generating the proposal configurations x', v'. We then construct a loss that depends on the difference between x and x' which is then optimized during training. I guess it's not a purely generative approach as is typical for normalizing flows, but it makes use of the RealNVP architecture which is (from my understanding) really the basis of all these normalizing flow type approaches.
Is the paper targeted mostly at physicists? Besides some references to flow papers, normalizing flows don't appear to get mentioned in your manuscript.
Our initial experiments (https://arxiv.org/abs/2105.03418) are focused exclusively on looking at applying this approach to lattice gauge models, but our approach is generally applicable and works with any target distribution.
We do plan to submit an expanded, detailed submission which will be conventionally peer reviewed sometime in the near future, but I can't say with certainty when that will happen.
That's great! Perhaps we can reopen this issue once that's done?
yeah, no worries! I'll make sure to follow up then!
